<subSubSection pageId="139" pageNumber="536" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="139" pageNumber="536" targetBox="[167,758,299,713]" targetPageId="139">
<paragraph blockId="139.[781,1374,293,720]" pageId="139" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[782,958,569,602]" pageId="139" pageNumber="536">Distribution.</emphasis>
Scattered localities in NE Nigeria, N Cameroon, S Sudan, NW Ethiopia, NW Kenya, and S Somalia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="139" pageNumber="536" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="139.[781,1374,293,720]" box="[781,1370,695,720]" pageId="139" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[781,1031,695,720]" pageId="139" pageNumber="536">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 52-66 mm,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="139.[165,1372,730,1547]" pageId="139" pageNumber="536">tail 34-41 mm, ear 6-8 mm, hindfoot 9-10 mm; weight 4-5 g. The Yankari Whitetoothed Shrew is small, with short pelage. Dorsum is olive-brown (hairs are gray basally and brown-tipped), and ventral pelage is smoky gray or grayish olive (hairs are uniformly gray) and merges with dorsum on flanks with little delineation. Lower parts of hindlimbs are unique without brownish hair. Ears are large and covered with fine hairs and stiff bristles on inner folds. Feet are white. Tail is ¢.67% of head—body length, hairy, and bicolored, being brown above and whitish below. Skull profile slopes gradually upward anteriorly. There are three unicuspids. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 68 and FN = 122.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="139" pageNumber="536" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="139.[165,1372,730,1547]" pageId="139" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[166,278,1081,1114]" pageId="139" pageNumber="536">Habitat.</emphasis>
Primarily dry savanna. A Yankari White-toothed Shrew was found in shrubs and boulders in wet grasslands in Ethiopia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
